{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11922"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11922"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.11,0.02,0.02,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"1698"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of worsening scrotal pain. The pain is constant in nature and came on gradually. On further history, he mentions that he has been feeling increasingly fatigued for the past few months and has had an increased urge to urinate at night time. He works as a truck driver and does not have a regular GP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, pulse 105/min and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. Scrotal examination reveals a diffusely erythematous and swollen scrotum and perineum which is exquisitely painful to palpation (Image). An intravenous line is inserted and broad spectrum antibiotics started.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urine and blood cultures","Scrotal ultrasound","CT scan","Tissue biopsy","Surgical debridement"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with Fournier\u0027s gangrene, a form of necrotising fasciitis of the perineum and scrotum. Fournier\u0027s gangrene is a bacterial infection of the fascia which can rapidly spread throughout the soft tissue of the abdomen and perineum, causing necrosis, extensive tissue loss, and can become a life-threatening infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis man is at increased risk for developing Fournier\u0027s gangrene given his job as a truck driver, which predisposes him to local infections around the perineum that can precipitate into necrotising fasciitis. Furthermore, his history of fatigue and nocturia in the context of poor medical follow up is suspicious for underlying diabetes, which is another common risk factor for developing Fournier\u0027s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is a emergency - the first step in his management is get fluid resuscitation underway and administer antibiotics, followed by urgent \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical debridement \u003C/strong\u003Eof the scrotum and adjacent tissues. This should be done as soon as possible to identify and remove all necrotic tissue to minimise spread and preserve tissues in the area, including the anus and penis, and to minimise the risk of death. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile imaging (e.g. via \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan)\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in cases of diagnostic doubt (such as identifying gas in the soft tissues) and perhaps to assess how far the infection has spread into adjacent tissues, this should not delay emergency surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBroad spectrum intravenous antibiotics should be commenced immediately. Whilst\u003Cstrong\u003E blood and urine cultures\u003C/strong\u003E may be done, they are not going to affect the decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this stage there is no indication for \u003Cstrong\u003Etissue biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E - that will be provided at the time of debridement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fournier\u0027s gangrene is a life-threatening infection that should be managed aggressively with broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics, and emergency surgical debridement.","Early recognition and intervention are crucial in managing necrotising fasciitis to prevent mortality and morbidity."],"references":["Kessler CS, Bauml J. Non-traumatic urologic emergencies in men: a clinical review. West J Emerg Med. 2009 Nov;10(4):281-7. PMID: 20046251; PMCID: PMC2791735. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2791735/","Voelzke BB, Hagedorn JC. Presentation and Diagnosis of Fournier Gangrene. Urology. 2018 Apr;114:8-13. doi: 10.1016/j.urology.2017.10.031. Epub 2017 Nov 13. PMID: 29146218. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29146218/","Leslie SW, Rad J, Foreman J. Fournier Gangrene. 2023 Jun 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31747228. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31747228/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11922"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17546"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17546"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5559d5a5-ac89-4d1a-94cc-1ca79908e9f1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5559d5a5-ac89-4d1a-94cc-1ca79908e9f1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":297,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T19:30:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T19:31:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"att